  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Primary Health Care for IDPs in Erbil and Ninewa</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">This project will provide primary healthcare and vital health education to displaced people in northern Iraq. AMAR has been providing primary healthcare to IDPs since the beginning of the current crisis in 2014. 

This proposal is to fund 3 Primary Health Care Centres (PHCCs) in Mamilian IDP camp, Baharka village and Essian IDP camp. These PHCCs serve catchment areas of nearly 45,000 people in Erbil and Ninewa governorates in camp and non-camp locations, including minority groups such as Yazidis, Christians and Shabak. These PHCCs for IDPs lack funding and are at risk of closure without support from the IHPF.

The PHCCs see approximately equal numbers of men and women and are designed to ensure that the needs of both genders are understood and met, including providing health professions of both genders to ensure that men and women feel comfortable. The PHCCs additionally have facilities to address gendered health problems and include maternal health and reproductive health clinics for women. AMAR also runs an outreach programme of health education aimed specifically to reach women, the Women Health Volunteer (WHV) programme. 

The PHCCs also address the different needs of people at different ages, including child health care. AMAR monitors growth and weight of children to screen for malnutrition. 

Finally, the PHCCs see many patients with disabilities. In some cases, where people have fled following fighting in the Mosul corridor, the PHCC sees many patients with severe injuries. WHVs can form an important link to the PHCC for patients with mobility difficulties. In other cases, disability can be related to mental health. These PHCCs are part of AMAR&#x2019;s Escaping Darkness project that mainstreams mental health care into primary health care provision by training and supporting GPs and community workers.</narrative>
  </description>
